Docs.summary: The Compilation object is an immutable representation of a single invocation of the compiler. Although immutable, a Compilation is also on-demand, in that a compilation can be created quickly, but will that compiler parts or all of the code in order to respond to method or properties. Also, a compilation can produce a new compilation with a small change from the current compilation. This is, in many cases, more efficient than creating a new compilation from scratch, as the new compilation can share information from the old compilation.

Docs.summary: Creates a new compilation with the specified references.
Docs.remarks:
The new will query the given for the underlying metadata as soon as the are needed.
The New compilation uses whatever metadata is currently being provided by the . E.g. if the current compilation references a metadata file that has changed since the creation of the compilation the New compilation is going to use the updated version, while the current compilation will be using the previous (it doesn't change).
